TFTP and NFS setup document for BBB:

Essential commands:
lsusb         - list usb devices, look for FTDI on a host for BBB connection
ip link       - list all active and inactive network interfaces on host
hostname -I   - list host's ip addr, use if you are connecting BBB to router via ether


------TFTP SETUP------

1. Use setenv command on BBB uboot interface to set the following:
setenv ipaddr 192.168.0.100
setenv serverip 192.168.0.1
setenv ethprime usb_ether      		 if using usb to power BBB, or eth0 for ethernet connection to router is given
setenv usbnet_devaddr f8:dc:7a:00:00:02  (MAC addr on BBB side)
setenv usbnet_hostaddr f8:dc:7a:00:00:01  (MAC addr on HOST side) //experimenting with setting to actual host mac addr
	
2. Saveenv on Uboot, running ping serverip on Uboot while running ifconfig on host side
	will show a new interface has been connected to the host.

3. On host pc, run 'nmcli con add type ethernet ifname enxf8dc7a000001 ip4 192.168.0.1/24'
	-this command will NOT override the dynamic dhcp given to the host by the router,
		instead, it will use this ip when communicating with the enx device(BBB)
	-verify with 'nmcli connection show', remove with 'nmcli connection delete [connection name]'

4. Run sudo apt install tftpd-hpa on host pc, then nano /etc/default/tftpd-hpa
	-edit the directory to be a new tftp folder in the /home/user/ directory
	-should look like:
		# /etc/default/tftpd-hpa

		TFTP_USERNAME="tftp"
		TFTP_DIRECTORY="/home/kishore/tftpBBB"
		TFTP_ADDRESS="0.0.0.0:69"
		TFTP_OPTIONS="--secure"
	-run exportfs -a to save tftp setting changes

5. Run:
	-sudo systemctl restart tftpd-hpa
	-sudo systemctl status tftpd-hpa
	-sudo chmod 755 tftp_folder
	-sudo chmod -R 644 tftp_folder/files_in_this_folder
		-add zimage and .dtb files here and do chmod on those files
	-After running chmod permission changes, you can test the changes by:
		-create text.txt in the tftp folder
		-run 'tftp 0x81000000 text.txt' on BBB uboot
		-run 'md 0x81000000' on BBB uboot to see memory contents

6. Ensure firewall ufw disabled.

------NFS SETUP------


1. The following commands should be executed to set up nfs server:

	-sudo mkdir ~/nfsroot
	-sudo apt-get install nfs-kernel-server
	-sudo nano /etc/exports    <--edit file to add nfs root directory:
		/home/user/nfsroot 192.168.0.100(rw,sync,insecure,no_subtree_check,no_root_squash) 
		or alternatively: add a * instead of the ip, to make it accessible by all ips
	-sudo exportfs -a
	-sudo systemctl restart nfs-kernel-server

2. The following changes must be reflected in the buildroot kernel .config file, 
	make this change by using 'nano .config' in the buildroot/output/build/linux-[version] directory:

	CONFIG_NFS_FS=y (NFS client support)
	CONFIG_ROOT_NFS=y (support for NFS as rootfs)
	CONFIG_IP_PNP=y (configure IP at boot time)    //optional, only if you want this
	
	Add options to support USB host and networking over USB device:
	–CONFIG_USB=y
	–CONFIG_USB_GADGET=y
	–CONFIG_USB_MUSB_HDRC=y Driver for the USB OTG controller
	–CONFIG_USB_MUSB_DSPS=y
	–CONFIG_USB_MUSB_DUAL_ROLE=y 
	-Check the dependencies of CONFIG_AM335X_PHY_USB and find the way to set 
		CONFIG_AM335X_PHY_USB=y
	–CONFIG_USB_ETH=y

3. Run:
	-sudo chmod 755 nfs_folder
		-the files in this folder can be generated by buildroot as a rootfs.tar
		-unzip the tar file here(tar -xavf file.tar) and change the permissions of the top folder nfsroot

testing:
setup uboot makemenuconfig changes and check if BBB can boot from emmc
set usb host mac addr to actual server mac address and observe the change

---Setup the uboot environment for booting tftp/nfs---

1. The following are uboot commands to setup the environment on BBB for booting: replace user with username

setenv bootfile zImage
setenv fdtfile am335x-boneblack.dtb
setenv loadaddr 0x82000000
setenv fdtaddr 0x88000000

setenv bootargs 'console=ttyS0,115200n8 root=/dev/nfs rw rootfstype=ext4 rootwait'
setenv set_tftp_nfs_bootargs 'setenv bootargs console=ttyS0,115200n8 root=/dev/nfs rw rootwait ip=${ipaddr}:::::usb0 g_ether.dev_addr=${usbnet_devaddr} g_ether.host_addr=${usbnet_hostaddr} nfsroot=${nfsrootpc},nfsvers=3,tcp'
setenv nfsrootpc ${serverip}:/home/user/nfsroot
setenv set_tftp_nfs_loadimage 'tftp ${loadaddr} ${bootfile}'
setenv set_tftp_nfs_loadfdt 'tftp ${fdtaddr} ${fdtfile}'
setenv uenvcmd_tftp_nfs 'ping ${serverip}; run set_tftp_nfs_bootargs; run set_tftp_nfs_loadimage; run set_tftp_nfs_loadfdt; printenv bootargs; bootz ${loadaddr} - ${fdtaddr}'



2. Running TFTP - NFS booted BBB

::::::RUNNING TFTP_NFS BOOT:::::::
HOST:
sudo systemctl start tftpd-hpa
sudo systemctl restart tftpd-hpa
sudo systemctl restart nfs-kernel-server
sudo systemctl status nfs-kernel-server

BBB:
--ping server from BBB(ping ${serverip}), should say alive (hostname -I to get host ip)
run uenvcmd_tftp_nfs

wait long time... login=root, password=set at the buildroot menu
